<paragraph blockId="5.[138,243,1004,1028]" box="[138,243,1004,1028]" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
<emphasis box="[138,243,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1052,1140]" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
The new species is characterized by having two distinct spots at middle and subapical portions of forewing costa. The related species 
<taxonomicName authority="(Westwood)" baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[702,976,1084,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Aethes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="787" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cnicana">
<emphasis box="[702,824,1084,1108]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">A. cnicana</emphasis>
(Westwood)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Razowski" authorityName="Razowski" authorityYear="1964" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Aethes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="787" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amurensis">
<emphasis box="[1040,1185,1084,1108]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">A. amurensis</emphasis>
Razowski
</taxonomicName>
have longer and distinct medial fascia reaching to the middle of costa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,259,1197,1221]" box="[138,259,1197,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
<emphasis box="[138,259,1197,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1245,1461]" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
<emphasis box="[138,327,1245,1269]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[215,309,1245,1269]" captionStart="Figures 1–3" captionStartId="5.[138,207,473,492]" captionTargetBox="[139,1183,133,437]" captionTargetId="figure-286@5.[139,1185,133,437]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1–3. Aethes bistigmatus sp. nov. (1) Adult. (2) Male genitalia. (3) Aedeagus. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4669035" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4669035/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">Figure 1</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Wingspan 14.5 mm in male. Forewing ground colour pale grey or silverwhite; basal fascia indistinct, shortly elongated on costa, dark brown; median fascia developed on middle of costa, forming a small rectangular spot, then very weak towards dorsum, nearly indistinct, not arcuated; pre-apical streak similar to median fascia in shape and coloration; apex more or less rounded; termen very weakly oblique. Hindwing greyish brown, rather pale grey at basal area, showing a net-like pattern in the remaining area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1502,1685]" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
<emphasis box="[138,493,1502,1526]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[332,478,1502,1526]" captionStart="Figures 1–3" captionStartId="5.[138,207,473,492]" captionTargetBox="[139,1183,133,437]" captionTargetId="figure-286@5.[139,1185,133,437]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1–3. Aethes bistigmatus sp. nov. (1) Adult. (2) Male genitalia. (3) Aedeagus. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4669035" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4669035/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="787">Figures 2, 3</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Tegumen broad dorsally. Uncus atrophied. Socii not prominent, very slender, elongated. Transtilla with short and sub-triangular median process, shortly bifurcate terminally. Juxta rather small, narrow, nearly half-moon shaped, with rounded top. Valva short, rather broad at base, rounded near apex; sacculus narrowed, well sclerotized basally, reaching to middle of ventral margin of valva. Aedeagus stout, shortly pointed terminally, with numerous cornuti in vesica.
</paragraph>
